          "text": "Leo, the strongest counterargument: don’t invent an embedding representation now. That is phase-3 schema speculation. The bug is fully explained by one violated boundary: presentation metadata is being indexed as corpus text.\n\n**Confidence: high.** The current pipeline serializes `[user]` / `[assistant]` into `content`, normalizes that exact string, then derives `fts` from it. Both FTS and trigram therefore treat role labels as searchable terms. Snippets are generated from `content`, so labels can remain visible to the model and UI independently of retrieval. See [conversation-chunker.ts](/home/leon0399/Projects/llame/.claude/worktrees/fix-search-role-tag-leak/apps/api/src/search/chat/conversation-chunker.ts:51), [search schema](/home/leon0399/Projects/llame/.claude/worktrees/fix-search-role-tag-leak/apps/api/src/db/schema/search.ts:73), and [hybrid query](/home/leon0399/Projects/llame/.claude/worktrees/fix-search-role-tag-leak/apps/api/src/search/core/fusion.ts:223).\n\n```text\ncanonical messages\n       │\n       ├─ presentation content ── \"[user] hello\\n\\n[assistant] answer-1\"\n       │        └─ snippet / episodic-memory tool result\n       │\n       └─ retrieval content ───── \"hello\\n\\nanswer-1\"\n                └─ normalized_content ── \"hello answer-1\"\n                       └─ fts\n```\n\nRecommended design:\n\n- Keep `content` role-labelled. It is the model-facing/display representation. `search_conversations` already returns its snippet through the shared query path.\n- Make `normalized_content` derive from **role-free message text**, not `content`. It becomes the lexical representation used by FTS and trigrams.\n- Do not add `embedding_content` yet. When embeddings land, choose between role-aware and role-free input with the eval set—not intuition. The existing `content` is available for the former; canonical messages can regenerate either. Persist a third raw field only if Phase 3 demonstrates a real need for it.\n- Bump `CHUNKER_VERSION`. Otherwise historic projection rows retain poisoned vectors indefinitely; the existing stale-version discovery/reindex path is designed for this rebuild.\n\nThis preserves the needed model context: a result for query `hello` can surface `[user] hello [assistant] answer-1`, while queries `user` or `assistant` return nothing unless those words actually appear in the conversation body or title.\n\nAcceptance criteria worth locking before implementation:\n\n- A chunk’s `content` retains role labels; its `normalizedContent` and `fts` contain neither label.\n- `user` / `assistant` produce no content match for a corpus whose bodies do not contain those words.\n- Literal body text remains searchable: “the assistant should…” must still match `assistant`.\n- Returned snippets for genuine matches retain role attribution.\n- A reindex under the new chunker version removes tags from existing `normalized_content` / `fts`.\n- Tenant/RLS negative coverage remains unchanged.\n\nYour “multiple representations” instinct is correct, but the minimal durable version is two semantic representations plus the generated FTS vector—not three arbitrary text columns. The research rationale for role-marked chunks was about conversational context, not permission to contaminate every retrieval channel.\n\nPrioritized next step: create an OpenSpec proposal for a narrowly scoped `separate-search-and-presentation-projections` change, with the above invariants and migration/backfill behavior.",
